  "prompt": "How long does it take for teeth to relapse (move) after a broken retainer?",
  "response": "The amount of time it takes for teeth to relapse after a broken retainer can vary widely depending on several factors including the individual's age, the original position of the teeth, the duration and type of orthodontic treatment, and how long the retainer was worn before it broke.\n\nIn general, teeth can begin to shift within days to weeks after a retainer breaks or is no longer worn. For some people, noticeable movement might occur within a few days, while for others, it may take a few weeks to become apparent. The risk of relapse is particularly high if the teeth were recently moved or if the retainer was being worn full-time.\n\nIt is important to contact your orthodontist as soon as possible if your retainer breaks or is lost, so they can evaluate the situation and provide a replacement or alternative solution to prevent significant relapse.",
